2336  /// Abstract Attribute dependency graph
2337  AADepGraph DG;
2338 
2339  /// Set of functions for which we modified the content such that it might
2340  /// impact the call graph.
2341  SmallSetVector<Function *, 8> CGModifiedFunctions;
2342 
2343  /// Information about a dependence. If FromAA is changed ToAA needs to be
2344  /// updated as well.
2345  struct DepInfo {
2346  const AbstractAttribute *FromAA;
2347  const AbstractAttribute *ToAA;
2348  DepClassTy DepClass;
2349  };
2350 
2351  /// The dependence stack is used to track dependences during an
2352  /// `AbstractAttribute::update` call. As `AbstractAttribute::update` can be
2353  /// recursive we might have multiple vectors of dependences in here. The stack
2354  /// size, should be adjusted according to the expected recursion depth and the
2355  /// inner dependence vector size to the expected number of dependences per
2356  /// abstract attribute. Since the inner vectors are actually allocated on the
2357  /// stack we can be generous with their size.
2358  using DependenceVector = SmallVector<DepInfo, 8>;
2359  SmallVector<DependenceVector *, 16> DependenceStack;
2360 
2361  /// A set to remember the functions we already assume to be live and visited.
2362  DenseSet<const Function *> VisitedFunctions;
2363 
2364  /// Uses we replace with a new value after manifest is done. We will remove
2365  /// then trivially dead instructions as well.
2366  SmallMapVector<Use *, Value *, 32> ToBeChangedUses;
2367 
2368  /// Values we replace with a new value after manifest is done. We will remove
2369  /// then trivially dead instructions as well.
2370  SmallMapVector<Value *, PointerIntPair<Value *, 1, bool>, 32>
2371  ToBeChangedValues;
2372 
2373  /// Instructions we replace with `unreachable` insts after manifest is done.
2374  SmallSetVector<WeakVH, 16> ToBeChangedToUnreachableInsts;
2375 
2376  /// Invoke instructions with at least a single dead successor block.
2377  SmallSetVector<WeakVH, 16> InvokeWithDeadSuccessor;
2378 
2379  /// A flag that indicates which stage of the process we are in. Initially, the
2380  /// phase is SEEDING. Phase is changed in `Attributor::run()`
2381  enum class AttributorPhase {
2382  SEEDING,
2383  UPDATE,
2384  MANIFEST,
2385  CLEANUP,
2386  } Phase = AttributorPhase::SEEDING;
2387 
2388  /// The current initialization chain length. Tracked to avoid stack overflows.
2389  unsigned InitializationChainLength = 0;
2390 
2391  /// Functions, blocks, and instructions we delete after manifest is done.
2392  ///
2393  ///{
2394  SmallPtrSet<BasicBlock *, 8> ManifestAddedBlocks;
2395  SmallSetVector<Function *, 8> ToBeDeletedFunctions;
2396  SmallSetVector<BasicBlock *, 8> ToBeDeletedBlocks;
2397  SmallSetVector<WeakVH, 8> ToBeDeletedInsts;
2398  ///}
2399 
2400  /// Container with all the query AAs that requested an update via
2401  /// registerForUpdate.
2402  SmallSetVector<AbstractAttribute *, 16> QueryAAsAwaitingUpdate;
2403 
2404  /// User provided configuration for this Attributor instance.
2405  const AttributorConfig Configuration;
2406 
2407  friend AADepGraph;
2408  friend AttributorCallGraph;
2409 };
2410 
2411 /// An interface to query the internal state of an abstract attribute.
2412 ///
2413 /// The abstract state is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
2414 /// communicate with the abstract attributes about their internal state without
2415 /// enforcing or exposing implementation details, e.g., the (existence of an)
2416 /// underlying lattice.
2417 ///
2418 /// It is sufficient to be able to query if a state is (1) valid or invalid, (2)
2419 /// at a fixpoint, and to indicate to the state that (3) an optimistic fixpoint
2420 /// was reached or (4) a pessimistic fixpoint was enforced.
2421 ///
2422 /// All methods need to be implemented by the subclass. For the common use case,
2423 /// a single boolean state or a bit-encoded state, the BooleanState and
2424 /// {Inc,Dec,Bit}IntegerState classes are already provided. An abstract
2425 /// attribute can inherit from them to get the abstract state interface and
2426 /// additional methods to directly modify the state based if needed. See the
2427 /// class comments for help.
2428 struct AbstractState {
2429  virtual ~AbstractState() = default;
2430 
2431  /// Return if this abstract state is in a valid state. If false, no
2432  /// information provided should be used.
2433  virtual bool isValidState() const = 0;
2434 
2435  /// Return if this abstract state is fixed, thus does not need to be updated
2436  /// if information changes as it cannot change itself.
2437  virtual bool isAtFixpoint() const = 0;
2438 
2439  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the optimistic state.
2440  ///
2441  /// This will usually make the optimistically assumed state the known to be
2442  /// true state.
2443  ///
2444  /// \returns ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED as the assumed value should not change.
2445  virtual ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() = 0;
2446 
2447  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the pessimistic state.
2448  ///
2449  /// This will usually revert the optimistically assumed state to the known to
2450  /// be true state.
2451  ///
2452  /// \returns ChangeStatus::CHANGED as the assumed value may change.
2453  virtual ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() = 0;
2454 };
2455 
2456 /// Simple state with integers encoding.
2457 ///
2458 /// The interface ensures that the assumed bits are always a subset of the known
2459 /// bits. Users can only add known bits and, except through adding known bits,
2460 /// they can only remove assumed bits. This should guarantee monotoniticy and
2461 /// thereby the existence of a fixpoint (if used corretly). The fixpoint is
2462 /// reached when the assumed and known state/bits are equal. Users can
2463 /// force/inidicate a fixpoint. If an optimistic one is indicated, the known
2464 /// state will catch up with the assumed one, for a pessimistic fixpoint it is
2465 /// the other way around.
2466 template <typename base_ty, base_ty BestState, base_ty WorstState>
2467 struct IntegerStateBase : public AbstractState {
2468  using base_t = base_ty;
2469 
2470  IntegerStateBase() = default;
2471  IntegerStateBase(base_t Assumed) : Assumed(Assumed) {}
2472 
2473  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2474  static constexpr base_t getBestState() { return BestState; }
2475  static constexpr base_t getBestState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
2476  return getBestState();
2477  }
2478 
2479  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
2480  static constexpr base_t getWorstState() { return WorstState; }
2481  static constexpr base_t getWorstState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
2482  return getWorstState();
2483  }
2484 
2485  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2486  /// NOTE: For now we simply pretend that the worst possible state is invalid.
2487  bool isValidState() const override { return Assumed != getWorstState(); }
2488 
2489  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2490  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
2491 
2492  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2493  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2494  Known = Assumed;
2495  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2496  }
2497 
2498  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2499  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2500  Assumed = Known;
2501  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2502  }
2503 
2504  /// Return the known state encoding
2505  base_t getKnown() const { return Known; }
2506 
2507  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2508  base_t getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2509 
2510  /// Equality for IntegerStateBase.
2511  bool
2512  operator==(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
2513  return this->getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() &&
2514  this->getKnown() == R.getKnown();
2515  }
2516 
2517  /// Inequality for IntegerStateBase.
2518  bool
2519  operator!=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
2520  return !(*this == R);
2521  }
2522 
2523  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2524  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
2525  /// this one afterwards.
2526  void operator^=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2527  handleNewAssumedValue(R.getAssumed());
2528  }
2529 
2530  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2531  /// intended that information known in either state will be known in
2532  /// this one afterwards.
2533  void operator+=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2534  handleNewKnownValue(R.getKnown());
2535  }
2536 
2537  void operator|=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2538  joinOR(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
2539  }
2540 
2541  void operator&=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2542  joinAND(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
2543  }
2544 
2545 protected:
2546  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2547  virtual void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) = 0;
2548 
2549  /// Handle a new known value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2550  virtual void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) = 0;
2551 
2552  /// Handle a value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2553  virtual void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
2554 
2555  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2556  virtual void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
2557 
2558  /// The known state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
2559  base_t Known = getWorstState();
2560 
2561  /// The assumed state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
2562  base_t Assumed = getBestState();
2563 };
2564 
2565 /// Specialization of the integer state for a bit-wise encoding.
2566 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t, base_ty BestState = ~base_ty(0),
2567  base_ty WorstState = 0>
2568 struct BitIntegerState
2569  : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> {
2570  using base_t = base_ty;
2571 
2572  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "known bits".
2573  bool isKnown(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
2574  return (this->Known & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
2575  }
2576 
2577  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "assumed bits".
2578  bool isAssumed(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
2579  return (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
2580  }
2581 
2582  /// Add the bits in \p BitsEncoding to the "known bits".
2583  BitIntegerState &addKnownBits(base_t Bits) {
2584  // Make sure we never miss any "known bits".
2585  this->Assumed |= Bits;
2586  this->Known |= Bits;
2587  return *this;
2588  }
2589 
2590  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "assumed bits" if not known.
2591  BitIntegerState &removeAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2592  return intersectAssumedBits(~BitsEncoding);
2593  }
2594 
2595  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "known bits".
2596  BitIntegerState &removeKnownBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2597  this->Known = (this->Known & ~BitsEncoding);
2598  return *this;
2599  }
2600 
2601  /// Keep only "assumed bits" also set in \p BitsEncoding but all known ones.
2602  BitIntegerState &intersectAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2603  // Make sure we never loose any "known bits".
2604  this->Assumed = (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) | this->Known;
2605  return *this;
2606  }
2607 
2608 private:
2609  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2610  intersectAssumedBits(Value);
2611  }
2612  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { addKnownBits(Value); }
2613  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2614  this->Known |= KnownValue;
2615  this->Assumed |= AssumedValue;
2616  }
2617  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2618  this->Known &= KnownValue;
2619  this->Assumed &= AssumedValue;
2620  }
2621 };
2622 
2623 /// Specialization of the integer state for an increasing value, hence ~0u is
2624 /// the best state and 0 the worst.
2625 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t, base_ty BestState = ~base_ty(0),
2626  base_ty WorstState = 0>
2627 struct IncIntegerState
2628  : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> {
2629  using super = IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState>;
2630  using base_t = base_ty;
2631 
2632  IncIntegerState() : super() {}
2633  IncIntegerState(base_t Assumed) : super(Assumed) {}
2634 
2635  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2636  static constexpr base_t getBestState() { return BestState; }
2637  static constexpr base_t
2638  getBestState(const IncIntegerState<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> &) {
2639  return getBestState();
2640  }
2641 
2642  /// Take minimum of assumed and \p Value.
2643  IncIntegerState &takeAssumedMinimum(base_t Value) {
2644  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2645  this->Assumed = std::max(std::min(this->Assumed, Value), this->Known);
2646  return *this;
2647  }
2648 
2649  /// Take maximum of known and \p Value.
2650  IncIntegerState &takeKnownMaximum(base_t Value) {
2651  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2652  this->Assumed = std::max(Value, this->Assumed);
2653  this->Known = std::max(Value, this->Known);
2654  return *this;
2655  }
2656 
2657 private:
2658  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2659  takeAssumedMinimum(Value);
2660  }
2661  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { takeKnownMaximum(Value); }
2662  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2663  this->Known = std::max(this->Known, KnownValue);
2664  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2665  }
2666  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2667  this->Known = std::min(this->Known, KnownValue);
2668  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2669  }
2670 };
2671 
2672 /// Specialization of the integer state for a decreasing value, hence 0 is the
2673 /// best state and ~0u the worst.
2674 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t>
2675 struct DecIntegerState : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, 0, ~base_ty(0)> {
2676  using base_t = base_ty;
2677 
2678  /// Take maximum of assumed and \p Value.
2679  DecIntegerState &takeAssumedMaximum(base_t Value) {
2680  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2681  this->Assumed = std::min(std::max(this->Assumed, Value), this->Known);
2682  return *this;
2683  }
2684 
2685  /// Take minimum of known and \p Value.
2686  DecIntegerState &takeKnownMinimum(base_t Value) {
2687  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2688  this->Assumed = std::min(Value, this->Assumed);
2689  this->Known = std::min(Value, this->Known);
2690  return *this;
2691  }
2692 
2693 private:
2694  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2695  takeAssumedMaximum(Value);
2696  }
2697  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { takeKnownMinimum(Value); }
2698  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2699  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, KnownValue);
2700  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2701  }
2702  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2703  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, KnownValue);
2704  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2705  }
2706 };
2707 
2708 /// Simple wrapper for a single bit (boolean) state.
2709 struct BooleanState : public IntegerStateBase<bool, true, false> {
2710  using super = IntegerStateBase<bool, true, false>;
2711  using base_t = IntegerStateBase::base_t;
2712 
2713  BooleanState() = default;
2714  BooleanState(base_t Assumed) : super(Assumed) {}
2715 
2716  /// Set the assumed value to \p Value but never below the known one.
2717  void setAssumed(bool Value) { Assumed &= (Known | Value); }
2718 
2719  /// Set the known and asssumed value to \p Value.
2720  void setKnown(bool Value) {
2721  Known |= Value;
2722  Assumed |= Value;
2723  }
2724 
2725  /// Return true if the state is assumed to hold.
2726  bool isAssumed() const { return getAssumed(); }
2727 
2728  /// Return true if the state is known to hold.
2729  bool isKnown() const { return getKnown(); }
2730 
2731 private:
2732  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2733  if (!Value)
2734  Assumed = Known;
2735  }
2736  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override {
2737  if (Value)
2738  Known = (Assumed = Value);
2739  }
2740  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2741  Known |= KnownValue;
2742  Assumed |= AssumedValue;
2743  }
2744  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2745  Known &= KnownValue;
2746  Assumed &= AssumedValue;
2747  }
2748 };
2749 
2750 /// State for an integer range.
2751 struct IntegerRangeState : public AbstractState {
2752 
2753  /// Bitwidth of the associated value.
2754  uint32_t BitWidth;
2755 
2756  /// State representing assumed range, initially set to empty.
2757  ConstantRange Assumed;
2758 
2759  /// State representing known range, initially set to [-inf, inf].
2760  ConstantRange Known;
2761 
2762  IntegerRangeState(uint32_t BitWidth)
2763  : BitWidth(BitWidth), Assumed(ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth)),
2764  Known(ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth)) {}
2765 
2766  IntegerRangeState(const ConstantRange &CR)
2767  : BitWidth(CR.getBitWidth()), Assumed(CR),
2768  Known(getWorstState(CR.getBitWidth())) {}
2769 
2770  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
2771  static ConstantRange getWorstState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
2772  return ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth);
2773  }
2774 
2775  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2776  static ConstantRange getBestState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
2777  return ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth);
2778  }
2779  static ConstantRange getBestState(const IntegerRangeState &IRS) {
2780  return getBestState(IRS.getBitWidth());
2781  }
2782 
2783  /// Return associated values' bit width.
2784  uint32_t getBitWidth() const { return BitWidth; }
2785 
2786  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2787  bool isValidState() const override {
2788  return BitWidth > 0 && !Assumed.isFullSet();
2789  }
2790 
2791  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2792  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
2793 
2794  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2795  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2796  Known = Assumed;
2797  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2798  }
2799 
2800  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2801  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2802  Assumed = Known;
2803  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2804  }
2805 
2806  /// Return the known state encoding
2807  ConstantRange getKnown() const { return Known; }
2808 
2809  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2810  ConstantRange getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2811 
2812  /// Unite assumed range with the passed state.
2813  void unionAssumed(const ConstantRange &R) {
2814  // Don't loose a known range.
2815  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(R).intersectWith(Known);
2816  }
2817 
2818  /// See IntegerRangeState::unionAssumed(..).
2819  void unionAssumed(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2820  unionAssumed(R.getAssumed());
2821  }
2822 
2823  /// Intersect known range with the passed state.
2824  void intersectKnown(const ConstantRange &R) {
2825  Assumed = Assumed.intersectWith(R);
2826  Known = Known.intersectWith(R);
2827  }
2828 
2829  /// See IntegerRangeState::intersectKnown(..).
2830  void intersectKnown(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2831  intersectKnown(R.getKnown());
2832  }
2833 
2834  /// Equality for IntegerRangeState.
2835  bool operator==(const IntegerRangeState &R) const {
2836  return getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() && getKnown() == R.getKnown();
2837  }
2838 
2839  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2840  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
2841  /// this one afterwards.
2842  IntegerRangeState operator^=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2843  // NOTE: `^=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
2844  // take `union`.
2845  unionAssumed(R);
2846  return *this;
2847  }
2848 
2849  IntegerRangeState operator&=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2850  // NOTE: `&=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
2851  // take `union`.
2852  Known = Known.unionWith(R.getKnown());
2853  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(R.getAssumed());
2854  return *this;
2855  }
2856 };
2857 
2858 /// Simple state for a set.
2859 ///
2860 /// This represents a state containing a set of values. The interface supports
2861 /// modelling sets that contain all possible elements. The state's internal
2862 /// value is modified using union or intersection operations.
2863 template <typename BaseTy> struct SetState : public AbstractState {
2864  /// A wrapper around a set that has semantics for handling unions and
2865  /// intersections with a "universal" set that contains all elements.
2866  struct SetContents {
2867  /// Creates a universal set with no concrete elements or an empty set.
2868  SetContents(bool Universal) : Universal(Universal) {}
2869 
2870  /// Creates a non-universal set with concrete values.
2871  SetContents(const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Assumptions)
2872  : Universal(false), Set(Assumptions) {}
2873 
2874  SetContents(bool Universal, const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Assumptions)
2875  : Universal(Universal), Set(Assumptions) {}
2876 
2877  const DenseSet<BaseTy> &getSet() const { return Set; }
2878 
2879  bool isUniversal() const { return Universal; }
2880 
2881  bool empty() const { return Set.empty() && !Universal; }
2882 
2883  /// Finds A := A ^ B where A or B could be the "Universal" set which
2884  /// contains every possible attribute. Returns true if changes were made.
2885  bool getIntersection(const SetContents &RHS) {
2886  bool IsUniversal = Universal;
2887  unsigned Size = Set.size();
2888 
2889  // A := A ^ U = A
2890  if (RHS.isUniversal())
2891  return false;
2892 
2893  // A := U ^ B = B
2894  if (Universal)
2895  Set = RHS.getSet();
2896  else
2897  set_intersect(Set, RHS.getSet());
2898 
2899  Universal &= RHS.isUniversal();
2900  return IsUniversal != Universal || Size != Set.size();
2901  }
2902 
2903  /// Finds A := A u B where A or B could be the "Universal" set which
2904  /// contains every possible attribute. returns true if changes were made.
2905  bool getUnion(const SetContents &RHS) {
2906  bool IsUniversal = Universal;
2907  unsigned Size = Set.size();
2908 
2909  // A := A u U = U = U u B
2910  if (!RHS.isUniversal() && !Universal)
2911  set_union(Set, RHS.getSet());
2912 
2913  Universal |= RHS.isUniversal();
2914  return IsUniversal != Universal || Size != Set.size();
2915  }
2916 
2917  private:
2918  /// Indicates if this set is "universal", containing every possible element.
2919  bool Universal;
2920 
2921  /// The set of currently active assumptions.
2922  DenseSet<BaseTy> Set;
2923  };
2924 
2925  SetState() : Known(false), Assumed(true), IsAtFixedpoint(false) {}
2926 
2927  /// Initializes the known state with an initial set and initializes the
2928  /// assumed state as universal.
2929  SetState(const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Known)
2930  : Known(Known), Assumed(true), IsAtFixedpoint(false) {}
2931 
2932  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2933  bool isValidState() const override { return !Assumed.empty(); }
2934 
2935  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2936  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return IsAtFixedpoint; }
2937 
2938  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2939  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2940  IsAtFixedpoint = true;
2941  Known = Assumed;
2942  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2943  }
2944 
2945  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2946  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2947  IsAtFixedpoint = true;
2948  Assumed = Known;
2949  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2950  }
2951 
2952  /// Return the known state encoding.
2953  const SetContents &getKnown() const { return Known; }
2954 
2955  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2956  const SetContents &getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2957 
2958  /// Returns if the set state contains the element.
2959  bool setContains(const BaseTy &Elem) const {
2960  return Assumed.getSet().contains(Elem) || Known.getSet().contains(Elem);
2961  }
2962 
2963  /// Performs the set intersection between this set and \p RHS. Returns true if
2964  /// changes were made.
2965  bool getIntersection(const SetContents &RHS) {
2966  unsigned SizeBefore = Assumed.getSet().size();
2967 
2968  // Get intersection and make sure that the known set is still a proper
2969  // subset of the assumed set. A := K u (A ^ R).
2970  Assumed.getIntersection(RHS);
2971  Assumed.getUnion(Known);
2972 
2973  return SizeBefore != Assumed.getSet().size();
2974  }
2975 
2976  /// Performs the set union between this set and \p RHS. Returns true if
2977  /// changes were made.
2978  bool getUnion(const SetContents &RHS) { return Assumed.getUnion(RHS); }
2979 
2980 private:
2981  /// The set of values known for this state.
2982  SetContents Known;
2983 
2984  /// The set of assumed values for this state.
2985  SetContents Assumed;
2986 
2987  bool IsAtFixedpoint;
2988 };
2989

2994  const ArrayRef<Attribute> &DeducedAttrs,
2995  bool ForceReplace = false);
2996 };

2998 /// Helper to tie a abstract state implementation to an abstract attribute.
2999 template <typename StateTy, typename BaseType, class... Ts>
3000 struct StateWrapper : public BaseType, public StateTy {
3001  /// Provide static access to the type of the state.
3002  using StateType = StateTy;
3003 
3004  StateWrapper(const IRPosition &IRP, Ts... Args)
3005  : BaseType(IRP), StateTy(Args...) {}
3006 
3007  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
3008  StateType &getState() override { return *this; }
3009 
3010  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
3011  const StateType &getState() const override { return *this; }

3014 /// Helper class that provides common functionality to manifest IR attributes.
3015 template <Attribute::AttrKind AK, typename BaseType>
3016 struct IRAttribute : public BaseType {
3017  IRAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : BaseType(IRP) {}
3018 
3019  /// See AbstractAttribute::initialize(...).
3020  void initialize(Attributor &A) override {
3021  const IRPosition &IRP = this->getIRPosition();
3022  if (isa<UndefValue>(IRP.getAssociatedValue()) ||
3023  this->hasAttr(getAttrKind(), /* IgnoreSubsumingPositions */ false,
3024  &A)) {
3025  this->getState().indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3026  return;
3027  }
3028 
3029  bool IsFnInterface = IRP.isFnInterfaceKind();
3030  const Function *FnScope = IRP.getAnchorScope();
3031  // TODO: Not all attributes require an exact definition. Find a way to
3032  // enable deduction for some but not all attributes in case the
3033  // definition might be changed at runtime, see also
3034  // http://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2018-February/121275.html.
3035  // TODO: We could always determine abstract attributes and if sufficient
3036  // information was found we could duplicate the functions that do not
3037  // have an exact definition.
3038  if (IsFnInterface && (!FnScope || !A.isFunctionIPOAmendable(*FnScope)))
3039  this->getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3040  }
3041 
3042  /// See AbstractAttribute::manifest(...).
3043  ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) override {
3044  if (isa<UndefValue>(this->getIRPosition().getAssociatedValue()))
3045  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
3046  SmallVector<Attribute, 4> DeducedAttrs;
3047  getDeducedAttributes(this->getAnchorValue().getContext(), DeducedAttrs);
3048  return IRAttributeManifest::manifestAttrs(A, this->getIRPosition(),
3049  DeducedAttrs);
3050  }
3051 
3052  /// Return the kind that identifies the abstract attribute implementation.
3053  Attribute::AttrKind getAttrKind() const { return AK; }
3054 
3055  /// Return the deduced attributes in \p Attrs.
3056  virtual void getDeducedAttributes(LLVMContext &Ctx,
3057  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs) const {
3058  Attrs.emplace_back(Attribute::get(Ctx, getAttrKind()));
3059  }
3060 };
3061 
3062 /// Base struct for all "concrete attribute" deductions.
3063 ///
3064 /// The abstract attribute is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
3065 /// orchestrate the abstract/fixpoint analysis. The design allows to hide away
3066 /// implementation choices made for the subclasses but also to structure their
3067 /// implementation and simplify the use of other abstract attributes in-flight.
3068 ///
3069 /// To allow easy creation of new attributes, most methods have default
3070 /// implementations. The ones that do not are generally straight forward, except
3071 /// `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl` which is the location of most reasoning
3072 /// associated with the abstract attribute. The update is invoked by the
3073 /// Attributor in case the situation used to justify the current optimistic
3074 /// state might have changed. The Attributor determines this automatically
3075 /// by monitoring the `Attributor::getAAFor` calls made by abstract attributes.
3076 ///
3077 /// The `updateImpl` method should inspect the IR and other abstract attributes
3078 /// in-flight to justify the best possible (=optimistic) state. The actual
3079 /// implementation is, similar to the underlying abstract state encoding, not
3080 /// exposed. In the most common case, the `updateImpl` will go through a list of
3081 /// reasons why its optimistic state is valid given the current information. If
3082 /// any combination of them holds and is sufficient to justify the current
3083 /// optimistic state, the method shall return UNCHAGED. If not, the optimistic
3084 /// state is adjusted to the situation and the method shall return CHANGED.
3085 ///
3086 /// If the manifestation of the "concrete attribute" deduced by the subclass
3087 /// differs from the "default" behavior, which is a (set of) LLVM-IR
3088 /// attribute(s) for an argument, call site argument, function return value, or
3089 /// function, the `AbstractAttribute::manifest` method should be overloaded.
3090 ///
3091 /// NOTE: If the state obtained via getState() is INVALID, thus if
3092 /// AbstractAttribute::getState().isValidState() returns false, no
3093 /// information provided by the methods of this class should be used.
3094 /// NOTE: The Attributor currently has certain limitations to what we can do.
3095 /// As a general rule of thumb, "concrete" abstract attributes should *for
3096 /// now* only perform "backward" information propagation. That means
3097 /// optimistic information obtained through abstract attributes should
3098 /// only be used at positions that precede the origin of the information
3099 /// with regards to the program flow. More practically, information can
3100 /// *now* be propagated from instructions to their enclosing function, but
3101 /// *not* from call sites to the called function. The mechanisms to allow
3102 /// both directions will be added in the future.
3103 /// NOTE: The mechanics of adding a new "concrete" abstract attribute are
3104 /// described in the file comment.
3105 struct AbstractAttribute : public IRPosition, public AADepGraphNode {
3106  using StateType = AbstractState;
3107 
3108  AbstractAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : IRPosition(IRP) {}
3109 
3110  /// Virtual destructor.
3111  virtual ~AbstractAttribute() = default;
3112 
3113  /// This function is used to identify if an \p DGN is of type
3114  /// AbstractAttribute so that the dyn_cast and cast can use such information
3115  /// to cast an AADepGraphNode to an AbstractAttribute.
3116  ///
3117  /// We eagerly return true here because all AADepGraphNodes except for the
3118  /// Synthethis Node are of type AbstractAttribute
3119  static bool classof(const AADepGraphNode *DGN) { return true; }
3120 
3121  /// Initialize the state with the information in the Attributor \p A.
3122  ///
3123  /// This function is called by the Attributor once all abstract attributes
3124  /// have been identified. It can and shall be used for task like:
3125  /// - identify existing knowledge in the IR and use it for the "known state"
3126  /// - perform any work that is not going to change over time, e.g., determine
3127  /// a subset of the IR, or attributes in-flight, that have to be looked at
3128  /// in the `updateImpl` method.
3129  virtual void initialize(Attributor &A) {}
3130 
3131  /// A query AA is always scheduled as long as we do updates because it does
3132  /// lazy computation that cannot be determined to be done from the outside.
3133  /// However, while query AAs will not be fixed if they do not have outstanding
3134  /// dependences, we will only schedule them like other AAs. If a query AA that
3135  /// received a new query it needs to request an update via
3136  /// `Attributor::requestUpdateForAA`.
3137  virtual bool isQueryAA() const { return false; }
3138 
3139  /// Return the internal abstract state for inspection.
3140  virtual StateType &getState() = 0;
3141  virtual const StateType &getState() const = 0;
3142 
3143  /// Return an IR position, see struct IRPosition.
3144  const IRPosition &getIRPosition() const { return *this; };
3145  IRPosition &getIRPosition() { return *this; };
3146 
3147  /// Helper functions, for debug purposes only.
3148  ///{
3149  void print(raw_ostream &OS) const override;
3150  virtual void printWithDeps(raw_ostream &OS) const;
3151  void dump() const { print(dbgs()); }
3152 
3153  /// This function should return the "summarized" assumed state as string.
3154  virtual const std::string getAsStr() const = 0;
3155 
3156  /// This function should return the name of the AbstractAttribute
3157  virtual const std::string getName() const = 0;
3158 
3159  /// This function should return the address of the ID of the AbstractAttribute
3160  virtual const char *getIdAddr() const = 0;
3161  ///}
3162 
3163  /// Allow the Attributor access to the protected methods.
3164  friend struct Attributor;
3165 
3166 protected:
3167  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger an update of the internal state.
3168  ///
3169  /// If this attribute is already fixed, this method will return UNCHANGED,
3170  /// otherwise it delegates to `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl`.
3171  ///
3172  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
3173  ChangeStatus update(Attributor &A);
3174 
3175  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger the manifestation of the information
3176  /// represented by the abstract attribute in the LLVM-IR.
3177  ///
3178  /// \Return CHANGED if the IR was altered, otherwise UNCHANGED.
3179  virtual ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) {
3180  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
3181  }
3182 
3183  /// Hook to enable custom statistic tracking, called after manifest that
3184  /// resulted in a change if statistics are enabled.
3185  ///
3186  /// We require subclasses to provide an implementation so we remember to
3187  /// add statistics for them.
3188  virtual void trackStatistics() const = 0;
3189 
3190  /// The actual update/transfer function which has to be implemented by the
3191  /// derived classes.
3192  ///
3193  /// If it is called, the environment has changed and we have to determine if
3194  /// the current information is still valid or adjust it otherwise.
3195  ///
3196  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
3197  virtual ChangeStatus updateImpl(Attributor &A) = 0;
3198 };

3201 ///
3202 ///{
3203 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const AbstractAttribute &AA);
3204 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, ChangeStatus S);
3205 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, IRPosition::Kind);
3206 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const IRPosition &);
3207 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const AbstractState &State);

3209 raw_ostream &

3229 /// Helper function to clamp a state \p S of type \p StateType with the
3230 /// information in \p R and indicate/return if \p S did change (as-in update is
3231 /// required to be run again).
3232 template <typename StateType>
3233 ChangeStatus clampStateAndIndicateChange(StateType &S, const StateType &R) {
3234  auto Assumed = S.getAssumed();
3235  S ^= R;
3236  return Assumed == S.getAssumed() ? ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED
3237  : ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
3238 }

3614 /// An abstract interface for liveness abstract attribute.
3615 struct AAIsDead
3616  : public StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint8_t, 3, 0>, AbstractAttribute> {
3617  using Base = StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint8_t, 3, 0>, AbstractAttribute>;
3618  AAIsDead(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
3619 
3620  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
3621  enum {
3622  HAS_NO_EFFECT = 1 << 0,
3623  IS_REMOVABLE = 1 << 1,
3624 
3625  IS_DEAD = HAS_NO_EFFECT | IS_REMOVABLE,
3626  };
3627  static_assert(IS_DEAD == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
3628 
3629 protected:
3630  /// The query functions are protected such that other attributes need to go
3631  /// through the Attributor interfaces: `Attributor::isAssumedDead(...)`
3632 
3633  /// Returns true if the underlying value is assumed dead.
3634  virtual bool isAssumedDead() const = 0;
3635 
3636  /// Returns true if the underlying value is known dead.
3637  virtual bool isKnownDead() const = 0;
3638 
3639  /// Returns true if \p BB is known dead.
3640  virtual bool isKnownDead(const BasicBlock *BB) const = 0;
3641 
3642  /// Returns true if \p I is assumed dead.
3643  virtual bool isAssumedDead(const Instruction *I) const = 0;
3644 
3645  /// Returns true if \p I is known dead.
3646  virtual bool isKnownDead(const Instruction *I) const = 0;
3647 
3648  /// Return true if the underlying value is a store that is known to be
3649  /// removable. This is different from dead stores as the removable store
3650  /// can have an effect on live values, especially loads, but that effect
3651  /// is propagated which allows us to remove the store in turn.
3652  virtual bool isRemovableStore() const { return false; }
3653 
3654  /// This method is used to check if at least one instruction in a collection
3655  /// of instructions is live.
3656  template <typename T> bool isLiveInstSet(T begin, T end) const {
3657  for (const auto &I : llvm::make_range(begin, end)) {
3658  assert(I->getFunction() == getIRPosition().getAssociatedFunction() &&
3659  "Instruction must be in the same anchor scope function.");
3660 
3661  if (!isAssumedDead(I))
3662  return true;
3663  }
3664 
3665  return false;
3666  }
3667 
3668 public:
3669  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3670  static AAIsDead &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
3671 
3672  /// Determine if \p F might catch asynchronous exceptions.
3673  static bool mayCatchAsynchronousExceptions(const Function &F) {
3674  return F.hasPersonalityFn() && !canSimplifyInvokeNoUnwind(&F);
3675  }
3676 
3677  /// Returns true if \p BB is assumed dead.
3678  virtual bool isAssumedDead(const BasicBlock *BB) const = 0;
3679 
3680  /// Return if the edge from \p From BB to \p To BB is assumed dead.
3681  /// This is specifically useful in AAReachability.
3682  virtual bool isEdgeDead(const BasicBlock *From, const BasicBlock *To) const {
3683  return false;
3684  }
3685 
3686  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
3687  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAIsDead"; }
3688 
3689  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
3690  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
3691 
3692  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AAIsDead
3693  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3694  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3695  }
3696 
3697  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
3698  static const char ID;
3699 
3700  friend struct Attributor;
3701 };
3702 
3703 /// State for dereferenceable attribute
3704 struct DerefState : AbstractState {
3705 
3706  static DerefState getBestState() { return DerefState(); }
3707  static DerefState getBestState(const DerefState &) { return getBestState(); }
3708 
3709  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
3710  static DerefState getWorstState() {
3711  DerefState DS;
3712  DS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3713  return DS;
3714  }
3715  static DerefState getWorstState(const DerefState &) {
3716  return getWorstState();
3717  }
3718 
3719  /// State representing for dereferenceable bytes.
3720  IncIntegerState<> DerefBytesState;
3721 
3722  /// Map representing for accessed memory offsets and sizes.
3723  /// A key is Offset and a value is size.
3724  /// If there is a load/store instruction something like,
3725  /// p[offset] = v;
3726  /// (offset, sizeof(v)) will be inserted to this map.
3727  /// std::map is used because we want to iterate keys in ascending order.
3728  std::map<int64_t, uint64_t> AccessedBytesMap;
3729 
3730  /// Helper function to calculate dereferenceable bytes from current known
3731  /// bytes and accessed bytes.
3732  ///
3733  /// int f(int *A){
3734  /// *A = 0;
3735  /// *(A+2) = 2;
3736  /// *(A+1) = 1;
3737  /// *(A+10) = 10;
3738  /// }
3739  /// ```
3740  /// In that case, AccessedBytesMap is `{0:4, 4:4, 8:4, 40:4}`.
3741  /// AccessedBytesMap is std::map so it is iterated in accending order on
3742  /// key(Offset). So KnownBytes will be updated like this:
3743  ///
3744  /// |Access | KnownBytes
3745  /// |(0, 4)| 0 -> 4
3746  /// |(4, 4)| 4 -> 8
3747  /// |(8, 4)| 8 -> 12
3748  /// |(40, 4) | 12 (break)
3749  void computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap() {
3750  int64_t KnownBytes = DerefBytesState.getKnown();
3751  for (auto &Access : AccessedBytesMap) {
3752  if (KnownBytes < Access.first)
3753  break;
3754  KnownBytes = std::max(KnownBytes, Access.first + (int64_t)Access.second);
3755  }
3756 
3757  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(KnownBytes);
3758  }
3759 
3760  /// State representing that whether the value is globaly dereferenceable.
3761  BooleanState GlobalState;
3762 
3763  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
3764  bool isValidState() const override { return DerefBytesState.isValidState(); }
3765 
3766  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
3767  bool isAtFixpoint() const override {
3768  return !isValidState() ||
3769  (DerefBytesState.isAtFixpoint() && GlobalState.isAtFixpoint());
3770  }
3771 
3772  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
3773  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
3774  DerefBytesState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3775  GlobalState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3776  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
3777  }
3778 
3779  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
3780  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
3781  DerefBytesState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3782  GlobalState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3783  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
3784  }
3785 
3786  /// Update known dereferenceable bytes.
3787  void takeKnownDerefBytesMaximum(uint64_t Bytes) {
3788  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(Bytes);
3789 
3790  // Known bytes might increase.
3791  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
3792  }
3793 
3794  /// Update assumed dereferenceable bytes.
3795  void takeAssumedDerefBytesMinimum(uint64_t Bytes) {
3796  DerefBytesState.takeAssumedMinimum(Bytes);
3797  }
3798 
3799  /// Add accessed bytes to the map.
3800  void addAccessedBytes(int64_t Offset, uint64_t Size) {
3801  uint64_t &AccessedBytes = AccessedBytesMap[Offset];
3802  AccessedBytes = std::max(AccessedBytes, Size);
3803 
3804  // Known bytes might increase.
3805  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
3806  }
3807 
3808  /// Equality for DerefState.
3809  bool operator==(const DerefState &R) const {
3810  return this->DerefBytesState == R.DerefBytesState &&
3811  this->GlobalState == R.GlobalState;
3812  }
3813 
3814  /// Inequality for DerefState.
3815  bool operator!=(const DerefState &R) const { return !(*this == R); }
3816 
3817  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator^=
3818  DerefState operator^=(const DerefState &R) {
3819  DerefBytesState ^= R.DerefBytesState;
3820  GlobalState ^= R.GlobalState;
3821  return *this;
3822  }
3823 
3824  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator+=
3825  DerefState operator+=(const DerefState &R) {
3826  DerefBytesState += R.DerefBytesState;
3827  GlobalState += R.GlobalState;
3828  return *this;
3829  }
3830 
3831  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator&=
3832  DerefState operator&=(const DerefState &R) {
3833  DerefBytesState &= R.DerefBytesState;
3834  GlobalState &= R.GlobalState;
3835  return *this;
3836  }
3837 
3838  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator|=
3839  DerefState operator|=(const DerefState &R) {
3840  DerefBytesState |= R.DerefBytesState;
3841  GlobalState |= R.GlobalState;
3842  return *this;
3843  }
3844 
3845 protected:
3846  const AANonNull *NonNullAA = nullptr;
3847 };
3848

3975 /// An abstract interface for all nocapture attributes.
3976 struct AANoCapture
3977  : public IRAttribute<
3978  Attribute::NoCapture,
3979  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint16_t, 7, 0>, AbstractAttribute>> {
3980  AANoCapture(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
3981 
3982  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
3983  /// NO_CAPTURE is the best possible state, 0 the worst possible state.
3984  enum {
3985  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM = 1 << 0,
3986  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT = 1 << 1,
3987  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_RET = 1 << 2,
3988 
3989  /// If we do not capture the value in memory or through integers we can only
3990  /// communicate it back as a derived pointer.
3991  NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED = NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT,
3992 
3993  /// If we do not capture the value in memory, through integers, or as a
3994  /// derived pointer we know it is not captured.
3995  NO_CAPTURE =
3996  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_RET,
3997  };
3998 
3999  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not captured in its
4000  /// respective scope.
4001  bool isKnownNoCapture() const { return isKnown(NO_CAPTURE); }
4002 
4003  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not captured in its
4004  /// respective scope.
4005  bool isAssumedNoCapture() const { return isAssumed(NO_CAPTURE); }
4006 
4007  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not captured in its
4008  /// respective scope but we allow it to escape through a "return".
4009  bool isKnownNoCaptureMaybeReturned() const {
4010  return isKnown(NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED);
4011  }
4012 
4013  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not captured in its
4014  /// respective scope but we allow it to escape through a "return".
4015  bool isAssumedNoCaptureMaybeReturned() const {
4016  return isAssumed(NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED);
4017  }
4018 
4019  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4020  static AANoCapture &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
4021 
4022  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4023  const std::string getName() const override { return "AANoCapture"; }
4024 
4025  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4026  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4027 
4028  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AANoCapture
4029  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4030  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4031  }
4032 
4033  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4034  static const char ID;
4035 };

4037 struct ValueSimplifyStateType : public AbstractState {
4038 
4039  ValueSimplifyStateType(Type *Ty) : Ty(Ty) {}
4040 
4041  static ValueSimplifyStateType getBestState(Type *Ty) {
4042  return ValueSimplifyStateType(Ty);
4043  }
4044  static ValueSimplifyStateType getBestState(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
4045  return getBestState(VS.Ty);
4046  }
4047 
4048  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
4049  static ValueSimplifyStateType getWorstState(Type *Ty) {
4050  ValueSimplifyStateType DS(Ty);
4051  DS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4052  return DS;
4053  }
4054  static ValueSimplifyStateType
4055  getWorstState(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
4056  return getWorstState(VS.Ty);
4057  }
4058 
4059  /// See AbstractState::isValidState(...)
4060  bool isValidState() const override { return BS.isValidState(); }
4061 
4062  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint(...)
4063  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return BS.isAtFixpoint(); }
4064 
4065  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
4066  ValueSimplifyStateType getAssumed() { return *this; }
4067  const ValueSimplifyStateType &getAssumed() const { return *this; }
4068 
4069  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
4070  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
4071  return BS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4072  }
4073 
4074  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
4075  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
4076  return BS.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
4077  }
4078 
4079  /// "Clamp" this state with \p PVS.
4080  ValueSimplifyStateType operator^=(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
4081  BS ^= VS.BS;
4082  unionAssumed(VS.SimplifiedAssociatedValue);
4083  return *this;
4084  }
4085 
4086  bool operator==(const ValueSimplifyStateType &RHS) const {
4087  if (isValidState() != RHS.isValidState())
4088  return false;
4089  if (!isValidState() && !RHS.isValidState())
4090  return true;
4091  return SimplifiedAssociatedValue == RHS.SimplifiedAssociatedValue;
4092  }
4093 
4094 protected:
4095  /// The type of the original value.
4096  Type *Ty;
4097 
4098  /// Merge \p Other into the currently assumed simplified value
4099  bool unionAssumed(std::optional<Value *> Other);
4100 
4101  /// Helper to track validity and fixpoint
4102  BooleanState BS;
4103 
4104  /// An assumed simplified value. Initially, it is set to std::nullopt, which
4105  /// means that the value is not clear under current assumption. If in the
4106  /// pessimistic state, getAssumedSimplifiedValue doesn't return this value but
4107  /// returns orignal associated value.
4108  std::optional<Value *> SimplifiedAssociatedValue;
4109 };

4111 /// An abstract interface for value simplify abstract attribute.
4112 struct AAValueSimplify
4113  : public StateWrapper<ValueSimplifyStateType, AbstractAttribute, Type *> {
4114  using Base = StateWrapper<ValueSimplifyStateType, AbstractAttribute, Type *>;
4115  AAValueSimplify(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A)
4116  : Base(IRP, IRP.getAssociatedType()) {}
4117 
4118  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4119  static AAValueSimplify &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4120  Attributor &A);
4121 
4122  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4123  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAValueSimplify"; }
4124 
4125  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4126  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4127 
4128  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4129  /// AAValueSimplify
4130  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4131  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4132  }
4133 
4134  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4135  static const char ID;
4136 
4137 private:
4138  /// Return an assumed simplified value if a single candidate is found. If
4139  /// there cannot be one, return original value. If it is not clear yet, return
4140  /// std::nullopt.
4141  ///
4142  /// Use `Attributor::getAssumedSimplified` for value simplification.
4143  virtual std::optional<Value *>
4144  getAssumedSimplifiedValue(Attributor &A) const = 0;
4145 
4146  friend struct Attributor;
4147 };

4178 /// An abstract interface for privatizability.
4179 ///
4180 /// A pointer is privatizable if it can be replaced by a new, private one.
4181 /// Privatizing pointer reduces the use count, interaction between unrelated
4182 /// code parts.
4183 ///
4184 /// In order for a pointer to be privatizable its value cannot be observed
4185 /// (=nocapture), it is (for now) not written (=readonly & noalias), we know
4186 /// what values are necessary to make the private copy look like the original
4187 /// one, and the values we need can be loaded (=dereferenceable).
4188 struct AAPrivatizablePtr
4189  : public StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute> {
4190  using Base = StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute>;
4191  AAPrivatizablePtr(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
4192 
4193  /// Returns true if pointer privatization is assumed to be possible.
4194  bool isAssumedPrivatizablePtr() const { return getAssumed(); }
4195 
4196  /// Returns true if pointer privatization is known to be possible.
4197  bool isKnownPrivatizablePtr() const { return getKnown(); }
4198 
4199  /// Return the type we can choose for a private copy of the underlying
4200  /// value. std::nullopt means it is not clear yet, nullptr means there is
4201  /// none.
4202  virtual std::optional<Type *> getPrivatizableType() const = 0;
4203 
4204  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4205  static AAPrivatizablePtr &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4206  Attributor &A);
4207 
4208  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4209  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAPrivatizablePtr"; }
4210 
4211  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4212  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4213 
4214  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4215  /// AAPricatizablePtr
4216  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4217  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4218  }
4219 
4220  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4221  static const char ID;
4222 };

4224 /// An abstract interface for memory access kind related attributes
4225 /// (readnone/readonly/writeonly).
4226 struct AAMemoryBehavior
4227  : public IRAttribute<
4228  Attribute::ReadNone,
4229  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint8_t, 3>, AbstractAttribute>> {
4230  AAMemoryBehavior(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
4231 
4232  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
4233  /// BEST_STATE is the best possible state, 0 the worst possible state.
4234  enum {
4235  NO_READS = 1 << 0,
4236  NO_WRITES = 1 << 1,
4237  NO_ACCESSES = NO_READS | NO_WRITES,
4238 
4239  BEST_STATE = NO_ACCESSES,
4240  };
4241  static_assert(BEST_STATE == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
4242 
4243  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not read or accessed
4244  /// in its respective scope.
4245  bool isKnownReadNone() const { return isKnown(NO_ACCESSES); }
4246 
4247  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not read or accessed
4248  /// in its respective scope.
4249  bool isAssumedReadNone() const { return isAssumed(NO_ACCESSES); }
4250 
4251  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not accessed
4252  /// (=written) in its respective scope.
4253  bool isKnownReadOnly() const { return isKnown(NO_WRITES); }
4254 
4255  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not accessed
4256  /// (=written) in its respective scope.
4257  bool isAssumedReadOnly() const { return isAssumed(NO_WRITES); }
4258 
4259  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not read in its
4260  /// respective scope.
4261  bool isKnownWriteOnly() const { return isKnown(NO_READS); }
4262 
4263  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not read in its
4264  /// respective scope.
4265  bool isAssumedWriteOnly() const { return isAssumed(NO_READS); }
4266 
4267  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4268  static AAMemoryBehavior &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4269  Attributor &A);
4270 
4271  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4272  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAMemoryBehavior"; }
4273 
4274  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4275  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4276 
4277  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4278  /// AAMemoryBehavior
4279  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4280  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4281  }
4282 
4283  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4284  static const char ID;
4285 };

4287 /// An abstract interface for all memory location attributes
4288 /// (readnone/argmemonly/inaccessiblememonly/inaccessibleorargmemonly).
4289 struct AAMemoryLocation
4290  : public IRAttribute<
4291  Attribute::ReadNone,
4292  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint32_t, 511>, AbstractAttribute>> {
4293  using MemoryLocationsKind = StateType::base_t;
4294 
4295  AAMemoryLocation(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
4296 
4297  /// Encoding of different locations that could be accessed by a memory
4298  /// access.
4299  enum {
4300  ALL_LOCATIONS = 0,
4301  NO_LOCAL_MEM = 1 << 0,
4302  NO_CONST_MEM = 1 << 1,
4303  NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 2,
4304  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 3,
4305  NO_GLOBAL_MEM = NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM,
4306  NO_ARGUMENT_MEM = 1 << 4,
4307  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM = 1 << 5,
4308  NO_MALLOCED_MEM = 1 << 6,
4309  NO_UNKOWN_MEM = 1 << 7,
4310  NO_LOCATIONS = NO_LOCAL_MEM | NO_CONST_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM |
4311  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM |
4312  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_MALLOCED_MEM | NO_UNKOWN_MEM,
4313 
4314  // Helper bit to track if we gave up or not.
4315  VALID_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS + 1,
4316 
4317  BEST_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS | VALID_STATE,
4318  };
4319  static_assert(BEST_STATE == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
4320 
4321  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has no observable
4322  /// accesses.
4323  bool isKnownReadNone() const { return isKnown(NO_LOCATIONS); }
4324 
4325  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has no observable
4326  /// accesses.
4327  bool isAssumedReadNone() const {
4328  return isAssumed(NO_LOCATIONS) || isAssumedStackOnly();
4329  }
4330 
4331  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has at most
4332  /// local/stack accesses.
4333  bool isKnowStackOnly() const {
4334  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
4335  }
4336 
4337  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has at most
4338  /// local/stack accesses.
4339  bool isAssumedStackOnly() const {
4340  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
4341  }
4342 
4343  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4344  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
4345  bool isKnownInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
4346  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
4347  }
4348 
4349  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4350  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
4351  bool isAssumedInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
4352  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
4353  }
4354 
4355  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4356  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
4357  bool isKnownArgMemOnly() const {
4358  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4359  }
4360 
4361  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4362  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
4363  bool isAssumedArgMemOnly() const {
4364  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4365  }
4366 
4367  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4368  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
4369  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
4370  bool isKnownInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
4371  return isKnown(
4372  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4373  }
4374 
4375  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4376  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
4377  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
4378  bool isAssumedInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
4379  return isAssumed(
4380  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4381  }
4382 
4383  /// Return true if the underlying value may access memory through arguement
4384  /// pointers of the associated function, if any.
4385  bool mayAccessArgMem() const { return !isAssumed(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM); }
4386 
4387  /// Return true if only the memory locations specififed by \p MLK are assumed
4388  /// to be accessed by the associated function.
4389  bool isAssumedSpecifiedMemOnly(MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const {
4390  return isAssumed(MLK);
4391  }
4392 
4393  /// Return the locations that are assumed to be not accessed by the associated
4394  /// function, if any.
4395  MemoryLocationsKind getAssumedNotAccessedLocation() const {
4396  return getAssumed();
4397  }
4398 
4399  /// Return the inverse of location \p Loc, thus for NO_XXX the return
4400  /// describes ONLY_XXX. The flags \p AndLocalMem and \p AndConstMem determine
4401  /// if local (=stack) and constant memory are allowed as well. Most of the
4402  /// time we do want them to be included, e.g., argmemonly allows accesses via
4403  /// argument pointers or local or constant memory accesses.
4404  static MemoryLocationsKind
4405  inverseLocation(MemoryLocationsKind Loc, bool AndLocalMem, bool AndConstMem) {
4406  return NO_LOCATIONS & ~(Loc | (AndLocalMem ? NO_LOCAL_MEM : 0) |
4407  (AndConstMem ? NO_CONST_MEM : 0));
4408  };
4409 
4410  /// Return the locations encoded by \p MLK as a readable string.
4411  static std::string getMemoryLocationsAsStr(MemoryLocationsKind MLK);
4412 
4413  /// Simple enum to distinguish read/write/read-write accesses.
4414  enum AccessKind {
4415  NONE = 0,
4416  READ = 1 << 0,
4417  WRITE = 1 << 1,
4418  READ_WRITE = READ | WRITE,
4419  };
4420 
4421  /// Check \p Pred on all accesses to the memory kinds specified by \p MLK.
4422  ///
4423  /// This method will evaluate \p Pred on all accesses (access instruction +
4424  /// underlying accessed memory pointer) and it will return true if \p Pred
4425  /// holds every time.
4426  virtual bool checkForAllAccessesToMemoryKind(
4427  function_ref<bool(const Instruction *, const Value *, AccessKind,
4428  MemoryLocationsKind)>
4429  Pred,
4430  MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const = 0;
4431 
4432  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4433  static AAMemoryLocation &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4434  Attributor &A);
4435 
4436  /// See AbstractState::getAsStr().
4437  const std::string getAsStr() const override {
4438  return getMemoryLocationsAsStr(getAssumedNotAccessedLocation());
4439  }
4440 
4441  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4442  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAMemoryLocation"; }
4443 
4444  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4445  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4446 
4447  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4448  /// AAMemoryLocation
4449  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4450  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4451  }
4452 
4453  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4454  static const char ID;
4455 };

4457 /// An abstract interface for range value analysis.

4497  }

4513 };
4514 
4515 /// A class for a set state.
4516 /// The assumed boolean state indicates whether the corresponding set is full
4517 /// set or not. If the assumed state is false, this is the worst state. The
4518 /// worst state (invalid state) of set of potential values is when the set
4519 /// contains every possible value (i.e. we cannot in any way limit the value
4520 /// that the target position can take). That never happens naturally, we only
4521 /// force it. As for the conditions under which we force it, see
4522 /// AAPotentialConstantValues.
4523 template <typename MemberTy> struct PotentialValuesState : AbstractState {
4524  using SetTy = SmallSetVector<MemberTy, 8>;
4525 
4526  PotentialValuesState() : IsValidState(true), UndefIsContained(false) {}
4527 
4528  PotentialValuesState(bool IsValid)
4529  : IsValidState(IsValid), UndefIsContained(false) {}
4530 
4531  /// See AbstractState::isValidState(...)
4532  bool isValidState() const override { return IsValidState.isValidState(); }
4533 
4534  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint(...)
4535  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return IsValidState.isAtFixpoint(); }
4536 
4537  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
4538  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
4539  return IsValidState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4540  }
4541 
4542  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
4543  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
4544  return IsValidState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
4545  }
4546 
4547  /// Return the assumed state
4548  PotentialValuesState &getAssumed() { return *this; }
4549  const PotentialValuesState &getAssumed() const { return *this; }
4550 
4551  /// Return this set. We should check whether this set is valid or not by
4552  /// isValidState() before calling this function.
4553  const SetTy &getAssumedSet() const {
4554  assert(isValidState() && "This set shoud not be used when it is invalid!");
4555  return Set;
4556  }
4557 
4558  /// Returns whether this state contains an undef value or not.
4559  bool undefIsContained() const {
4560  assert(isValidState() && "This flag shoud not be used when it is invalid!");
4561  return UndefIsContained;
4562  }
4563 
4564  bool operator==(const PotentialValuesState &RHS) const {
4565  if (isValidState() != RHS.isValidState())
4566  return false;
4567  if (!isValidState() && !RHS.isValidState())
4568  return true;
4569  if (undefIsContained() != RHS.undefIsContained())
4570  return false;
4571  return Set == RHS.getAssumedSet();
4572  }
4573 
4574  /// Maximum number of potential values to be tracked.
4575  /// This is set by -attributor-max-potential-values command line option
4576  static unsigned MaxPotentialValues;
4577 
4578  /// Return empty set as the best state of potential values.
4579  static PotentialValuesState getBestState() {
4580  return PotentialValuesState(true);
4581  }
4582 
4583  static PotentialValuesState getBestState(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4584  return getBestState();
4585  }
4586 
4587  /// Return full set as the worst state of potential values.
4588  static PotentialValuesState getWorstState() {
4589  return PotentialValuesState(false);
4590  }
4591 
4592  /// Union assumed set with the passed value.
4593  void unionAssumed(const MemberTy &C) { insert(C); }
4594 
4595  /// Union assumed set with assumed set of the passed state \p PVS.
4596  void unionAssumed(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) { unionWith(PVS); }
4597 
4598  /// Union assumed set with an undef value.
4599  void unionAssumedWithUndef() { unionWithUndef(); }
4600 
4601  /// "Clamp" this state with \p PVS.
4602  PotentialValuesState operator^=(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4603  IsValidState ^= PVS.IsValidState;
4604  unionAssumed(PVS);
4605  return *this;
4606  }
4607 
4608  PotentialValuesState operator&=(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4609  IsValidState &= PVS.IsValidState;
4610  unionAssumed(PVS);
4611  return *this;
4612  }
4613 
4614  bool contains(const MemberTy &V) const {
4615  return !isValidState() ? true : Set.contains(V);
4616  }
4617 
4618 protected:
4619  SetTy &getAssumedSet() {
4620  assert(isValidState() && "This set shoud not be used when it is invalid!");
4621  return Set;
4622  }
4623 
4624 private:
4625  /// Check the size of this set, and invalidate when the size is no
4626  /// less than \p MaxPotentialValues threshold.
4627  void checkAndInvalidate() {
4628  if (Set.size() >= MaxPotentialValues)
4629  indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4630  else
4631  reduceUndefValue();
4632  }
4633 
4634  /// If this state contains both undef and not undef, we can reduce
4635  /// undef to the not undef value.
4636  void reduceUndefValue() { UndefIsContained = UndefIsContained & Set.empty(); }
4637 
4638  /// Insert an element into this set.
4639  void insert(const MemberTy &C) {
4640  if (!isValidState())
4641  return;
4642  Set.insert(C);
4643  checkAndInvalidate();
4644  }
4645 
4646  /// Take union with R.
4647  void unionWith(const PotentialValuesState &R) {
4648  /// If this is a full set, do nothing.
4649  if (!isValidState())
4650  return;
4651  /// If R is full set, change L to a full set.
4652  if (!R.isValidState()) {
4653  indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4654  return;
4655  }
4656  for (const MemberTy &C : R.Set)
4657  Set.insert(C);
4658  UndefIsContained |= R.undefIsContained();
4659  checkAndInvalidate();
4660  }
4661 
4662  /// Take union with an undef value.
4663  void unionWithUndef() {
4664  UndefIsContained = true;
4665  reduceUndefValue();
4666  }
4667 
4668  /// Take intersection with R.
4669  void intersectWith(const PotentialValuesState &R) {
4670  /// If R is a full set, do nothing.
4671  if (!R.isValidState())
4672  return;
4673  /// If this is a full set, change this to R.
4674  if (!isValidState()) {
4675  *this = R;
4676  return;
4677  }
4678  SetTy IntersectSet;
4679  for (const MemberTy &C : Set) {
4680  if (R.Set.count(C))
4681  IntersectSet.insert(C);
4682  }
4683  Set = IntersectSet;
4684  UndefIsContained &= R.undefIsContained();
4685  reduceUndefValue();
4686  }
4687 
4688  /// A helper state which indicate whether this state is valid or not.
4689  BooleanState IsValidState;
4690 
4691  /// Container for potential values
4692  SetTy Set;
4693 
4694  /// Flag for undef value
4695  bool UndefIsContained;
4696 };
4697 
4698 using PotentialConstantIntValuesState = PotentialValuesState<APInt>;
4699 using PotentialLLVMValuesState =
4700  PotentialValuesState<std::pair<AA::ValueAndContext, AA::ValueScope>>;
4701 
4702 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS,
4703  const PotentialConstantIntValuesState &R);
4704 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const PotentialLLVMValuesState &R);
4705 
4706 /// An abstract interface for potential values analysis.
4707 ///
4708 /// This AA collects potential values for each IR position.
4709 /// An assumed set of potential values is initialized with the empty set (the
4710 /// best state) and it will grow monotonically as we find more potential values
4711 /// for this position.
4712 /// The set might be forced to the worst state, that is, to contain every
4713 /// possible value for this position in 2 cases.
4714 /// 1. We surpassed the \p MaxPotentialValues threshold. This includes the
4715 /// case that this position is affected (e.g. because of an operation) by a
4716 /// Value that is in the worst state.
4717 /// 2. We tried to initialize on a Value that we cannot handle (e.g. an
4718 /// operator we do not currently handle).
4719 ///
4720 /// For non constant integers see AAPotentialValues.
4721 struct AAPotentialConstantValues
4722  : public StateWrapper<PotentialConstantIntValuesState, AbstractAttribute> {
4723  using Base = StateWrapper<PotentialConstantIntValuesState, AbstractAttribute>;
4724  AAPotentialConstantValues(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
4725 
4726  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
4727  PotentialConstantIntValuesState &getState() override { return *this; }
4728  const PotentialConstantIntValuesState &getState() const override {
4729  return *this;
4730  }
4731 
4732  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4733  static AAPotentialConstantValues &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4734  Attributor &A);
4735 
4736  /// Return assumed constant for the associated value
4737  std::optional<Constant *>
4738  getAssumedConstant(Attributor &A, const Instruction *CtxI = nullptr) const {
4739  if (!isValidState())
4740  return nullptr;
4741  if (getAssumedSet().size() == 1) {
4742  Type *Ty = getAssociatedValue().getType();
4743  return cast_or_null<Constant>(AA::getWithType(
4744  *ConstantInt::get(Ty->getContext(), *(getAssumedSet().begin())),
4745  *Ty));
4746  }
4747  if (getAssumedSet().size() == 0) {
4748  if (undefIsContained())
4749  return UndefValue::get(getAssociatedValue().getType());
4750  return std::nullopt;
4751  }
4752 
4753  return nullptr;
4754  }
4755 
4756  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4757  const std::string getName() const override {
4758  return "AAPotentialConstantValues";
4759  }
4760 
4761  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4762  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4763 
4764  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4765  /// AAPotentialConstantValues
4766  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4767  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4768  }
4769 
4770  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4771  static const char ID;
4772 };
