5114 /// An abstract interface for struct information.
5115 struct AAPointerInfo : public AbstractAttribute {
5116  AAPointerInfo(const IRPosition &IRP) : AbstractAttribute(IRP) {}
5117 
5118  enum AccessKind {
5119  // First two bits to distinguish may and must accesses.
5120  AK_MUST = 1 << 0,
5121  AK_MAY = 1 << 1,
5122 
5123  // Then two bits for read and write. These are not exclusive.
5124  AK_R = 1 << 2,
5125  AK_W = 1 << 3,
5126  AK_RW = AK_R | AK_W,
5127 
5128  // One special case for assumptions about memory content. These
5129  // are neither reads nor writes. They are however always modeled
5130  // as read to avoid using them for write removal.
5131  AK_ASSUMPTION = (1 << 4) | AK_MUST,
5132 
5133  // Helper for easy access.
5134  AK_MAY_READ = AK_MAY | AK_R,
5135  AK_MAY_WRITE = AK_MAY | AK_W,
5136  AK_MAY_READ_WRITE = AK_MAY | AK_R | AK_W,
5137  AK_MUST_READ = AK_MUST | AK_R,
5138  AK_MUST_WRITE = AK_MUST | AK_W,
5139  AK_MUST_READ_WRITE = AK_MUST | AK_R | AK_W,
5140  };
5141 
5142  /// A container for a list of ranges.
5143  struct RangeList {
5144  // The set of ranges rarely contains more than one element, and is unlikely
5145  // to contain more than say four elements. So we find the middle-ground with
5146  // a sorted vector. This avoids hard-coding a rarely used number like "four"
5147  // into every instance of a SmallSet.
5148  using RangeTy = AA::RangeTy;
5149  using VecTy = SmallVector<RangeTy>;
5150  using iterator = VecTy::iterator;
5151  using const_iterator = VecTy::const_iterator;
5152  VecTy Ranges;
5153 
5154  RangeList(const RangeTy &R) { Ranges.push_back(R); }
5155  RangeList(ArrayRef<int64_t> Offsets, int64_t Size) {
5156  Ranges.reserve(Offsets.size());
5157  for (unsigned i = 0, e = Offsets.size(); i != e; ++i) {
5158  assert(((i + 1 == e) || Offsets[i] < Offsets[i + 1]) &&
5159  "Expected strictly ascending offsets.");
5160  Ranges.emplace_back(Offsets[i], Size);
5161  }
5162  }
5163  RangeList() = default;
5164 
5165  iterator begin() { return Ranges.begin(); }
5166  iterator end() { return Ranges.end(); }
5167  const_iterator begin() const { return Ranges.begin(); }
5168  const_iterator end() const { return Ranges.end(); }
5169 
5170  // Helpers required for std::set_difference
5171  using value_type = RangeTy;
5172  void push_back(const RangeTy &R) {
5173  assert((Ranges.empty() || RangeTy::OffsetLessThan(Ranges.back(), R)) &&
5174  "Ensure the last element is the greatest.");
5175  Ranges.push_back(R);
5176  }
5177 
5178  /// Copy ranges from \p L that are not in \p R, into \p D.
5179  static void set_difference(const RangeList &L, const RangeList &R,
5180  RangeList &D) {
5181  std::set_difference(L.begin(), L.end(), R.begin(), R.end(),
5182  std::back_inserter(D), RangeTy::OffsetLessThan);
5183  }
5184 
5185  unsigned size() const { return Ranges.size(); }
5186 
5187  bool operator==(const RangeList &OI) const { return Ranges == OI.Ranges; }
5188 
5189  /// Merge the ranges in \p RHS into the current ranges.
5190  /// - Merging a list of unknown ranges makes the current list unknown.
5191  /// - Ranges with the same offset are merged according to RangeTy::operator&
5192  /// \return true if the current RangeList changed.
5193  bool merge(const RangeList &RHS) {
5194  if (isUnknown())
5195  return false;
5196  if (RHS.isUnknown()) {
5197  setUnknown();
5198  return true;
5199  }
5200 
5201  if (Ranges.empty()) {
5202  Ranges = RHS.Ranges;
5203  return true;
5204  }
5205 
5206  bool Changed = false;
5207  auto LPos = Ranges.begin();
5208  for (auto &R : RHS.Ranges) {
5209  auto Result = insert(LPos, R);
5210  if (isUnknown())
5211  return true;
5212  LPos = Result.first;
5213  Changed |= Result.second;
5214  }
5215  return Changed;
5216  }
5217 
5218  /// Insert \p R at the given iterator \p Pos, and merge if necessary.
5219  ///
5220  /// This assumes that all ranges before \p Pos are OffsetLessThan \p R, and
5221  /// then maintains the sorted order for the suffix list.
5222  ///
5223  /// \return The place of insertion and true iff anything changed.
5224  std::pair<iterator, bool> insert(iterator Pos, const RangeTy &R) {
5225  if (isUnknown())
5226  return std::make_pair(Ranges.begin(), false);
5227  if (R.offsetOrSizeAreUnknown()) {
5228  return std::make_pair(setUnknown(), true);
5229  }
5230 
5231  // Maintain this as a sorted vector of unique entries.
5232  auto LB = std::lower_bound(Pos, Ranges.end(), R, RangeTy::OffsetLessThan);
5233  if (LB == Ranges.end() || LB->Offset != R.Offset)
5234  return std::make_pair(Ranges.insert(LB, R), true);
5235  bool Changed = *LB != R;
5236  *LB &= R;
5237  if (LB->offsetOrSizeAreUnknown())
5238  return std::make_pair(setUnknown(), true);
5239  return std::make_pair(LB, Changed);
5240  }
5241 
5242  /// Insert the given range \p R, maintaining sorted order.
5243  ///
5244  /// \return The place of insertion and true iff anything changed.
5245  std::pair<iterator, bool> insert(const RangeTy &R) {
5246  return insert(Ranges.begin(), R);
5247  }
5248 
5249  /// Add the increment \p Inc to the offset of every range.
5250  void addToAllOffsets(int64_t Inc) {
5251  assert(!isUnassigned() &&
5252  "Cannot increment if the offset is not yet computed!");
5253  if (isUnknown())
5254  return;
5255  for (auto &R : Ranges) {
5256  R.Offset += Inc;
5257  }
5258  }
5259 
5260  /// Return true iff there is exactly one range and it is known.
5261  bool isUnique() const {
5262  return Ranges.size() == 1 && !Ranges.front().offsetOrSizeAreUnknown();
5263  }
5264 
5265  /// Return the unique range, assuming it exists.
5266  const RangeTy &getUnique() const {
5267  assert(isUnique() && "No unique range to return!");
5268  return Ranges.front();
5269  }
5270 
5271  /// Return true iff the list contains an unknown range.
5272  bool isUnknown() const {
5273  if (isUnassigned())
5274  return false;
5275  if (Ranges.front().offsetOrSizeAreUnknown()) {
5276  assert(Ranges.size() == 1 && "Unknown is a singleton range.");
5277  return true;
5278  }
5279  return false;
5280  }
5281 
5282  /// Discard all ranges and insert a single unknown range.
5283  iterator setUnknown() {
5284  Ranges.clear();
5285  Ranges.push_back(RangeTy::getUnknown());
5286  return Ranges.begin();
5287  }
5288 
5289  /// Return true if no ranges have been inserted.
5290  bool isUnassigned() const { return Ranges.size() == 0; }
5291  };
5292 
5293  /// An access description.
5294  struct Access {
5295  Access(Instruction *I, int64_t Offset, int64_t Size,
5296  std::optional<Value *> Content, AccessKind Kind, Type *Ty)
5297  : LocalI(I), RemoteI(I), Content(Content), Ranges(Offset, Size),
5298  Kind(Kind), Ty(Ty) {
5299  verify();
5300  }
5301  Access(Instruction *LocalI, Instruction *RemoteI, const RangeList &Ranges,
5302  std::optional<Value *> Content, AccessKind K, Type *Ty)
5303  : LocalI(LocalI), RemoteI(RemoteI), Content(Content), Ranges(Ranges),
5304  Kind(K), Ty(Ty) {
5305  if (Ranges.size() > 1) {
5306  Kind = AccessKind(Kind | AK_MAY);
5307  Kind = AccessKind(Kind & ~AK_MUST);
5308  }
5309  verify();
5310  }
5311  Access(Instruction *LocalI, Instruction *RemoteI, int64_t Offset,
5312  int64_t Size, std::optional<Value *> Content, AccessKind Kind,
5313  Type *Ty)
5314  : LocalI(LocalI), RemoteI(RemoteI), Content(Content),
5315  Ranges(Offset, Size), Kind(Kind), Ty(Ty) {
5316  verify();
5317  }
5318  Access(const Access &Other) = default;
5319 
5320  Access &operator=(const Access &Other) = default;
5321  bool operator==(const Access &R) const {
5322  return LocalI == R.LocalI && RemoteI == R.RemoteI && Ranges == R.Ranges &&
5323  Content == R.Content && Kind == R.Kind;
5324  }
5325  bool operator!=(const Access &R) const { return !(*this == R); }
5326 
5327  Access &operator&=(const Access &R) {
5328  assert(RemoteI == R.RemoteI && "Expected same instruction!");
5329  assert(LocalI == R.LocalI && "Expected same instruction!");
5330 
5331  // Note that every Access object corresponds to a unique Value, and only
5332  // accesses to the same Value are merged. Hence we assume that all ranges
5333  // are the same size. If ranges can be different size, then the contents
5334  // must be dropped.
5335  Ranges.merge(R.Ranges);
5336  Content =
5337  AA::combineOptionalValuesInAAValueLatice(Content, R.Content, Ty);
5338 
5339  // Combine the access kind, which results in a bitwise union.
5340  // If there is more than one range, then this must be a MAY.
5341  // If we combine a may and a must access we clear the must bit.
5342  Kind = AccessKind(Kind | R.Kind);
5343  if ((Kind & AK_MAY) || Ranges.size() > 1) {
5344  Kind = AccessKind(Kind | AK_MAY);
5345  Kind = AccessKind(Kind & ~AK_MUST);
5346  }
5347  verify();
5348  return *this;
5349  }
5350 
5351  void verify() {
5352  assert(isMustAccess() + isMayAccess() == 1 &&
5353  "Expect must or may access, not both.");
5354  assert(isAssumption() + isWrite() <= 1 &&
5355  "Expect assumption access or write access, never both.");
5356  assert((isMayAccess() || Ranges.size() == 1) &&
5357  "Cannot be a must access if there are multiple ranges.");
5358  }
5359 
5360  /// Return the access kind.
5361  AccessKind getKind() const { return Kind; }
5362 
5363  /// Return true if this is a read access.
5364  bool isRead() const { return Kind & AK_R; }
5365 
5366  /// Return true if this is a write access.
5367  bool isWrite() const { return Kind & AK_W; }
5368 
5369  /// Return true if this is a write access.
5370  bool isWriteOrAssumption() const { return isWrite() || isAssumption(); }
5371 
5372  /// Return true if this is an assumption access.
5373  bool isAssumption() const { return Kind == AK_ASSUMPTION; }
5374 
5375  bool isMustAccess() const {
5376  bool MustAccess = Kind & AK_MUST;
5377  assert((!MustAccess || Ranges.size() < 2) &&
5378  "Cannot be a must access if there are multiple ranges.");
5379  return MustAccess;
5380  }
5381 
5382  bool isMayAccess() const {
5383  bool MayAccess = Kind & AK_MAY;
5384  assert((MayAccess || Ranges.size() < 2) &&
5385  "Cannot be a must access if there are multiple ranges.");
5386  return MayAccess;
5387  }
5388 
5389  /// Return the instruction that causes the access with respect to the local
5390  /// scope of the associated attribute.
5391  Instruction *getLocalInst() const { return LocalI; }
5392 
5393  /// Return the actual instruction that causes the access.
5394  Instruction *getRemoteInst() const { return RemoteI; }
5395 
5396  /// Return true if the value written is not known yet.
5397  bool isWrittenValueYetUndetermined() const { return !Content; }
5398 
5399  /// Return true if the value written cannot be determined at all.
5400  bool isWrittenValueUnknown() const {
5401  return Content.has_value() && !*Content;
5402  }
5403 
5404  /// Set the value written to nullptr, i.e., unknown.
5405  void setWrittenValueUnknown() { Content = nullptr; }
5406 
5407  /// Return the type associated with the access, if known.
5408  Type *getType() const { return Ty; }
5409 
5410  /// Return the value writen, if any.
5411  Value *getWrittenValue() const {
5412  assert(!isWrittenValueYetUndetermined() &&
5413  "Value needs to be determined before accessing it.");
5414  return *Content;
5415  }
5416 
5417  /// Return the written value which can be `llvm::null` if it is not yet
5418  /// determined.
5419  std::optional<Value *> getContent() const { return Content; }
5420 
5421  bool hasUniqueRange() const { return Ranges.isUnique(); }
5422  const AA::RangeTy &getUniqueRange() const { return Ranges.getUnique(); }
5423 
5424  /// Add a range accessed by this Access.
5425  ///
5426  /// If there are multiple ranges, then this is a "may access".
5427  void addRange(int64_t Offset, int64_t Size) {
5428  Ranges.insert({Offset, Size});
5429  if (!hasUniqueRange()) {
5430  Kind = AccessKind(Kind | AK_MAY);
5431  Kind = AccessKind(Kind & ~AK_MUST);
5432  }
5433  }
5434 
5435  const RangeList &getRanges() const { return Ranges; }
5436 
5437  using const_iterator = RangeList::const_iterator;
5438  const_iterator begin() const { return Ranges.begin(); }
5439  const_iterator end() const { return Ranges.end(); }
5440 
5441  private:
5442  /// The instruction responsible for the access with respect to the local
5443  /// scope of the associated attribute.
5444  Instruction *LocalI;
5445 
5446  /// The instruction responsible for the access.
5447  Instruction *RemoteI;
5448 
5449  /// The value written, if any. `llvm::none` means "not known yet", `nullptr`
5450  /// cannot be determined.
5451  std::optional<Value *> Content;
5452 
5453  /// Set of potential ranges accessed from the base pointer.
5454  RangeList Ranges;
5455 
5456  /// The access kind, e.g., READ, as bitset (could be more than one).
5457  AccessKind Kind;
5458 
5459  /// The type of the content, thus the type read/written, can be null if not
5460  /// available.
5461  Type *Ty;
5462  };
5463 
5464  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
5465  static AAPointerInfo &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
5466 
5467  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
5468  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAPointerInfo"; }
5469 
5470  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
5471  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
5472 
5473  /// Call \p CB on all accesses that might interfere with \p Range and return
5474  /// true if all such accesses were known and the callback returned true for
5475  /// all of them, false otherwise. An access interferes with an offset-size
5476  /// pair if it might read or write that memory region.
5477  virtual bool forallInterferingAccesses(
5478  AA::RangeTy Range, function_ref<bool(const Access &, bool)> CB) const = 0;
5479 
5480  /// Call \p CB on all accesses that might interfere with \p I and
5481  /// return true if all such accesses were known and the callback returned true
5482  /// for all of them, false otherwise. In contrast to forallInterferingAccesses
5483  /// this function will perform reasoning to exclude write accesses that cannot
5484  /// affect the load even if they on the surface look as if they would. The
5485  /// flag \p HasBeenWrittenTo will be set to true if we know that \p I does not
5486  /// read the intial value of the underlying memory.
5487  virtual bool forallInterferingAccesses(
5488  Attributor &A, const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA, Instruction &I,
5489  bool FindInterferingWrites, bool FindInterferingReads,
5490  function_ref<bool(const Access &, bool)> CB, bool &HasBeenWrittenTo,
5491  AA::RangeTy &Range) const = 0;
5492 
5493  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AAPointerInfo
5494  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
5495  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
5496  }
5497 
5498  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
5499  static const char ID;
5500 };
5501
